<br>
Bards and shammies potentially compete in the areas of slows and hastes. A shammy slow will almost always beat out a Bard slow, but you balance that against the fact that the bard slow also includes a snare component. In most cases, I defer to a shammy if there is one for slows, though sometimes I'll do what I call a &quot;pre-slow&quot; where I land mine early since I have less fear of generating aggro, and then watch for the shammy's to override mine (I see a premature wear off message, and, a good shammy usually announces it to boot), then I move that twist onto other things.<br>
<br>
Hastes are tougher. Shammy and bard haste vary in which is better depending on levels. At the highest level - particularly with a epic bard - bard haste wins. That said, some times you don't mind giving up a tiny bit of haste depending on how many melee's are benefitting and what the impact of a different song would be.<br>
<br>
You can bet that, in a group situation where I have any melee's to speak of, I'm going to be playing overhaste of some sort. If I have to cover regular haste too, then that means that 2 of my 3-4 twists are taken up just on haste, and there's a cost to that which needs to be weighed out a bit - every situation is a little different.<br>
<br>
BTW: If you're having any difficulty landing your slows, have your bard start out with Occlusion of Sound if they have it, or, if they are 42-54, have them use Chant of Disease - a Bard dot that has a disease debuff component (most shammy slows seem to be disease resist checks from what I can see - if yours is a different check, then have the bard adjust his/her chants accordingly). They may not want to stay with a chant, but if they start with one, you get that initial debuff until your slow lands. <p>Sing<br>
